What is Routing in Express.js?
Routing in Express.js is the mechanism that handles incoming HTTP requests and maps them to specific functions (controllers) based on the URL path and HTTP method.

Basic Routing Syntax
app.METHOD(PATH, HANDLER)

METHOD â†’ HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
PATH â†’ URL
HANDLER â†’ callback function

Example
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Home Page');
});

app.post('/login', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Login Success');
});


5ï¸âƒ£ Router-Level Routing (express.Router) â­â­â­
Used for modular and scalable apps.

const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

router.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('All users');
});

router.post('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Add user');
});

module.exports = router;

//**********
app.use('/users', router);


â“ What is express.Router()?
ğŸ‘‰ A mini Express app used to group routes


What is Middleware in Express.js?
Middleware is a function that has access to the request (req), response (res), and next() function, and it executes between the request and the response.

Middleware Function Syntax
(req, res, next) => {
  // logic
  next();
}

req â†’ request object
res â†’ response object
next() â†’ passes control to next middleware

Why Middleware is Used? (Interview â­)
Authentication & Authorization
Logging
Validation
Error handling
Request parsing
Code reusability


Middleware Execution Flow
Request â†’ Middleware 1 â†’ Middleware 2 â†’ Route Handler â†’ Response


Route-Specific Middleware
const auth = (req, res, next) => {
  if (!req.headers.authorization) {
    return res.status(401).send('Unauthorized');
  }
  next();
};

app.get('/dashboard', auth, (req, res) => {
  res.send('Welcome');
});


Multiple Middleware
app.get('/test', m1, m2, (req, res) => {
  res.send('Done');
});


What Happens If next() Is Not Called? âš ï¸
Request gets stuck
Response is never sent


Common Interview Questions & Answers
â“ What is next()?
ğŸ‘‰ Passes control to next middleware

â“ Order of middleware matters?
ğŸ‘‰ Yes, executed top-to-bottom

â“ Can middleware modify req/res?
ğŸ‘‰ Yes

â“ Can we send response in middleware?
ğŸ‘‰ Yes (authentication failure, errors)

One-Minute Interview Answer â­
Middleware in Express.js is a function that runs between the request and response. It can access req, res, and next(), 
and is used for tasks like authentication, logging, validation, and error handling.



What is Error Handling in Express.js?
Error handling in Express.js is the process of catching, managing, and responding to errors that occur during request processing, 
so the server doesnâ€™t crash and returns meaningful responses.

Why Error Handling is Important?
Prevents server crashes
Improves debugging
Returns proper HTTP status codes
Enhances user experience
Makes APIs production-ready


8ï¸âƒ£ How do you handle errors in Express?
Using error-handling middleware (err, req, res, next).

One-Minute Interview Answer â­
Error handling in Express.js is done using try-catch, next(err), and a special error-handling middleware with four parameters. 
It helps return proper responses and prevents server crashes.



What is CORS?
CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) is a security feature implemented by browsers that restricts web applications running on one origin (domain)
from accessing resources on another origin unless explicitly allowed by the server.

One-line interview answer â­
CORS is a mechanism to allow or restrict cross-origin HTTP requests in web applications.


Same-Origin Policy Example
Your frontend: http://localhost:3000
Your backend: http://localhost:5000

By default, frontend cannot make AJAX requests to backend because origins are different.


4ï¸âƒ£ CORS Options
methods â†’ allowed HTTP methods
allowedHeaders â†’ allowed headers
credentials â†’ send cookies

app.use(cors({
  origin: 'http://localhost:3000',
  methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT'],
  credentials: true
}));
